{
  "texts": [
    "First, they only appear when doping a correlated state away from charge neutrality; second, the states at |ν| = 0, 2, and 3 respectively have fan degeneracies of 4, 2, and 1 when the corresponding states are insulating or semimetallic in a given sample (there is usually no clear fan at |ν| = 1 as with rare exceptions there is never a strong insulator here).",
    "Both these features naturally emerge in the mean-field modelling of the IKS state [75].",
    "First, we find that the dispersion of the doped electrons is significantly flatter (more massive) when doping towards charge neutrality than when doping away from it.",
    "While the physical origins of this feature are probably better understood from the heavyfermion perspective of TBG, it is nevertheless present in the Hartree-Fock mean-field results on the continuum model.",
    "Second, studying the doping of the correlated IKS states at |ν| = 0, 2, and 3 indeed reproduces the fan degeneracy, as illustrated in Fig. 7."
  ]
}